content.problemStatement:
The `if` statement in Java is a conditional statement that allows the program to execute a block of code only if a specified condition evaluates to `true`.

**Syntax:**
```java
if (condition) {
    // Code to be executed if the condition is true
}
```
- If the condition evaluates to `true`, the block of code inside the `{}` is executed.
- If the condition evaluates to `false`, the block of code is skipped.

---
**Example**
```java
// Define a class named SEED-IT
class Seedit {
    // Main method: Entry point of the program
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Declare and initialize an integer variable
        int number = 10;

        // If statement to check if the number is greater than 0
        if (number > 0) {
            // If the condition is true, print the message
            System.out.println("The number is positive.");
        }
        // This statement will execute regardless of the if condition
        System.out.println("This statement always executes.");
    }
}
```
**Output:**
```default
The number is positive.
This statement always executes.
```

---
Curly braces `{}` are optional if there is only one statement inside the `if` block.

